    This place is like a modern day oasis. After trudging through a dilapidated alleyway, you see a light at the end of the tunnel. Walk through and you're instantly transported to a mesmerizing courtyard. The interior is astounding and luxuriously decorated but unfortunately the quality of the food isn't quite on par. It's a decent meal at best but I suppose one does not come here just for the food. Around 10pm the show starts and you're treated to a myriad of traditional musicians and dancers. It's a good way to spend the night and to experience a romanticized version of Morocco.

    Medina

    Hammam bath houses and covered spice and textile souks line the maze of cobblestoned lanes in the Medina, which occupies Marrakesh’s original fortified citadel. At night, Jemaa el-Fna square teems with snake charmers, folk dancers, and street food vendors serving all manner of food. Bahia Palace and Le Jardin Secret are 19th-century complexes open to the public, with ornate courtyards, mosaics, and gardens.
